04445nam a22007095i 9780691187211DE-B159720190523123322.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190523s2018    nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911872117 a10.1515/97806911872112doi  a(DE-B1597)501707  a(OCoLC)1076417308  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aDG295b.B62 2000eb 7aHIS0020202bisacsh04a937.07/092aB2231 aBoatwright, Mary T., eauthor.10aHadrian and the Cities of the Roman Empire /cMary T. Boatwright. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tCHAPTER 1. Roman Cities and Roman Power: The Roman Empire and Hadrian -- tCHAPTER 2. The Sources -- tCHAPTER 3. Changes of City Status and Their Impact on City Life -- tCHAPTER 4. Changes Affecting Cities' Daily Governance and Economy -- tCHAPTER 5. Civic Benefactions with Extramural Effects -- tCHAPTER 6. Engineering and Architectural Donations -- tCHAPTER 7. Athens, Smyrna, and Italica -- tCHAPTER 8. City Foundations, New and Renewed -- tCHAPTER 9. Hadrian'S Civic Benefactions and the Roman Empire -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tIndex  aCities throughout the Roman Empire flourished during the reign of Hadrian (A.D. 117-138), a phenomenon that not only strengthened and legitimized Roman dominion over its possessions but also revealed Hadrian as a masterful negotiator of power relationships. In this comprehensive investigation into the vibrant urban life that existed under Hadrian's rule, Mary T. Boatwright focuses on the emperor's direct interactions with Rome's cities, exploring the many benefactions for which he was celebrated on coins and in literary works and inscriptions. Although such evidence is often as imprecise as it is laudatory, its collective analysis, undertaken for the first time together with all other related material, reveals that over 130 cities received at least one benefaction directly from Hadrian. The benefactions, mediated by members of the empire's municipal elite, touched all aspects of urban life; they included imperial patronage of temples and hero tombs, engineering projects, promotion of athletic and cultural competitions, settlement of boundary disputes, and remission of taxes. Even as he manifested imperial benevolence, Hadrian reaffirmed the self-sufficiency and traditions of cities from Spain to Syria, the major exception being his harsh treatment of Jerusalem, which sparked the Third Jewish Revolt. Overall, the assembled evidence points to Hadrian's recognition of imperial munificence to cities as essential to the peace and prosperity of the empire. Boatwright's treatment of Hadrian and Rome's cities is unique in that it encompasses events throughout the empire, drawing insights from archaeology and art history as well as literature, economy, and religion.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Mai 2019) 0aCities and townszRome. 0aEmperorszRomevBiography. 0aPatron and clientzRome. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691187211zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780691187211.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG  aPDA9PRIN